title: For Sale:  Dillon XL 650 Progressive Reloader-$650 OBO
postcontent:
FOR SALE: New and never used Dillon XL 650 progressive reloader. This reloader comes with the following Dillon Precision Conversion Kits: Model # 21439 (300, 30-338, 308), Model # 21094 (308/30-06), and additional tool heads that were all purchased separately. No reloading dies with this machine as it did not come with them and this can be verified by Dillon's Precision Products, Inc., Blue Press book (as per the book reloading dies are sold separately). Also included is the manual and DVD to assist you in setting it all up. This is a package deal, and I do not need help in selling this reloader nor will I separate/ommit any of the items shown or listed. I will also not ship so local pickup only or I will meet you somewhere within a reasonable distance to Lincoln, NE. I am selling this for my Father and he is asking $650 OBO. Cash Only-No Exceptions. All reasonable offers (no lowball offers) will be considered.
Reloading with Dillon’s XL 650 (taken from Dillon Website)
Dillon’s XL650 is one of the easier progressive loaders in the world to learn to operate. Place a bullet onto the appropriate cartridge case in the XL650s shellplate. Lower the operating handle. The XL650 will automatically deprime and resize the case. It drops the next empty case to be inserted into the shellpIate, dispenses the powder charge, flares the case mouth, seats the bullet to its proper depth and crimps it tight. All automatically. All you touch is the operating handle. Lift the handle up. The XL650 will automatically rotate the shellplate to the next position, ejecting the loaded round into a convenient bin. It also pushes the next case into the shellplate.               
No Adjustments
Of all the steps in reloading, the adjustment of the reloading dies is the most critical. With the Dillon XL650s removable toolhead, your dies will stay in perfect adjustment. There’s no need to screw them in and out – even when changing calibers! The XL650 toolhead is held in place by two steel pins. There’s less to go wrong, less to remember.
